places called Walton, which are named with Old English <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Briton, serf’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>), <i>wald</i> ‘woodland’, <i>wall</i> ‘wall’, or <i>wælla</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","History: George Walton (1741–1804) signed the Declaration of Independence. He was born in Prince Edward County, VA, whither his grandfather had emigrated from England in 1682. He moved to Savannah, GA, and became governor of GA and a prominent jurist."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘Morning dew’; also ‘generosity’."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Anna Walton was born about 1100, in Gloucestershire, England. She married Sir Henry de Palmer I in 1140, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1149, in Stoke, Cheshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1100–1149":"umbes 1100–1149","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1122–1160":"1122–1160","1100–1149":"1100–1149","1106":"1106","1149":"1149","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1140":"1140","about 1100":"umbes 1100","1160":"1160","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1100–1149":"noin 1100–1149","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1122–1160":"1122–1160","1100–1149":"1100–1149","1106":"1106","1149":"1149","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1140":"1140","about 1100":"noin 1100","1160":"1160","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England"},"fr":{"about 1100–1149":"environ 1100–1149","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1122–1160":"1122–1160","1100–1149":"1100–1149","1106":"1106","1149":"1149","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1140":"1140","about 1100":"environ 1100","1160":"1160","Stoke, Cheshire, England":"Stoke, Cheshire, Angleterre","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lady Anna Walton est née environ 1100, à Gloucestershire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé Sir Henry de Palmer I en 1140, à Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée en 1149, à Stoke, Cheshire, Angleterre, à l